{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}} {{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}} {{Infobox person | name = Abdul Aziz Ghazi | image = File:Maulana_Aziz_1.jpg#/media/File:Maulana_Aziz_1.jpg | birth_date = {{Birth date|1963|1|10}} | birth_place = | death_date = | death_place = | nationality = [[Pakistan]] | spouse = | relations = | children = Hassan Ghazi | residence = [[Islamabad]], Pakistan | alma_mater = | occupation = Chancellor Of [[Jamia Hafsa]] And Imam Of [[Lal Masjid, Islamabad]] | known for = Pro-Taliban Sermons | signature = | website = | footnotes = }}
'''[[Mawlānā]] Abdul Aziz Ghazi''' ({{lang-ur|{{Nastaliq|محمد عبد العزيز}}}}) is a Pakistani cleric and [[khateeb]] ([[Khutbah|sermon]] giver) in the central mosque of [[Islamabad]] known as [[Lal Masjid, Islamabad|Lal Masjid]], which was the site of a [[Siege of Lal Masjid|siege]] in 2007 with the Pakistani army. Aziz was released from custody by the Pakistani supreme court in 2009 and acquitted in 2013. Besides being the Imam of [[Lal Masjid, Islamabad]] he is also the chancellor of [[Jamia Hafsa]]
In 2014, Aziz named a library at one of the mosque's seminaries after [[Osama Bin Laden]]<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.usnews.com/news/world/articles/2014/04/18/pakistani-madrassa-names-library-after-bin-laden |title=Pakistani madrassa names library after bin Laden |first=Munir |last=Ahmed |work=[[U.S. News & World Report]] |date=18 April 2014 |accessdate=22 October 2015}}</ref>
[[File:IMG-20151113-WA0010.jpg|thumb|Maulana Aziz Ghazi Addressing His Supporters]]
==Background== {{Deobandi}} Aziz came to [[Islamabad]] as a six-year-old boy from his home town in [[Balochistan (Pakistan)|Punjab]], when his father was appointed khateeb of Lal Masjid in 1966. He grew up in [[Islamabad]].{{Citation needed|date= June 2018}} Aziz is the son of [[Muhammad Abdullah Ghazi|Muhammad Abdullah]], the first prayer leader of Lal Masjid, and elder brother of [[Abdul Rashid Ghazi|Abdul Rashid]], who was killed in a government raid.{{Citation needed|date= June 2018}}
Aziz is descended from [[Sadwani]] [[clan]] of [[Mazari tribe|Mazari]] [[tribe]] in the town of [[Rojhan]] at the border of southern [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]] and [[Balochistan (Pakistan)|Balochistan]].{{Citation needed|date= June 2018}} Pakistan's military ruler, [[General Zia-ul-Haq]], was said to be very close to Abdullah.{{Citation needed|date= June 2018}}
==Education== After studying for few years in a public school, he was later sent to [[Karachi]] to study in a religious seminary. {{Citation needed|date= June 2018}} He is a graduate of [[Jamia Uloom-ul-Islamia]] Banuri Town, a [[Madrassah]] in Karachi, where he studied the customary [[Dars-e-Nizami]], which is taught at the most elementary level of religious education in [[Pakistan]].{{Citation needed|date= June 2018}}
After Graduating, The Government Appointed Him As [[Imam]] Of Islamabad's Mujaddiya Masjid In Sector F-8/2 , Where He Led Prayers Up Till (His Father) [[Muhammad Abdullah Ghazi|Maulana Abdullah Ghazi]]'s Assassination in 1998
==Lal Masjid==
Abdul Aziz served as officially designated prayer leader in Lal Masjid From 1998 until 2005 when he was dismissed from service (but never removed) after he issued a "[[fatwa]]" (religious decree) against the army officers who were fighting against the Taliban and their supporters in the tribal areas close to the Afghan border.{{Citation needed|date= June 2018}} In the fatwa he declared that none of the army officers who were killed in the fighting in tribal area was a [[martyr]] and religious sanctions were not available for their funeral. His fatwa irked the government and he was dismissed from service.{{Citation needed|date= June 2018}} But in fact, the government has not attempted to remove him from his post. A replacement cleric was appointed for Lal Masjid, but local Residents refused to pray behind anyone other than Aziz.
He closely followed the supreme leader of the [[Taliban]], [[Mohammed Omar|Mullah Omar]], and typically resisted being photographed.{{Citation needed|date= June 2018}}
Tensions between the government and religious students led by Abdul Aziz had simmered over the demolition of mosques. However, [[Islamabad]] was shaken out of its political stupor by the female students and teachers of the seminary in the last week of March.{{Citation needed|date= June 2018}} They announced the launch of a "moral drive" against all "immoral activities" in the federal capital.
He also warned the government of attacks in the case of a violent police operation launched against the seminary. "If the government fails to eradicate all these moral evils from the society within the specified period of one month the students of the seminary would themselves take actions against all the people involved in such activities," said Abdul Aziz while addressing Friday Prayer congregation at Lal Masjid.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.ohmynews.com/articleview/article_view.asp?menu=&no=354646&rel_no=1 |title=Religious Cleric Threatens Suicide Attacks |first=Umer |last=Farooq |work=[[OhmyNews International]] |date=7 April 2007 |accessdate=22 October 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305005909/http://english.ohmynews.com/articleview/article_view.asp?menu=&no=354646&rel_no=1 |archivedate=5 March 2016 }}</ref>
In his speech the cleric declared [[drugs]], music, movies, and photographs of women as moral evils.
=== Final Showdown ===
{{Main|Siege of Lal Masjid}}
The Lal Masjid brigade came to public notice when they kidnapped women (who they accused of being prostitutes) from Islamabad's residential areas and then later kidnapped several police officers.{{Citation needed|date= June 2018}} The brigade increased their activities and took to the crime of kidnapping Chinese workers from massage centres. This particular event created international pressure on Pakistan, especially from the Chinese government.{{Citation needed|date= June 2018}}
On 3 July 2007, the standoff with the government ended in bloody gun battles in which more than 1,000 Students were killed and scores wounded.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/world/2007/jul/04/pakistan.declanwalsh |title=Red Mosque leader attempts to flee in burka |first=Declan |last=Walsh |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=4 July 2007 |accessdate=22 October 2015}}</ref>
on 4 July 2007 at 8.05, Aziz was arrested while leaving the complex disguised in a [[burqa]]. , the reason for his cross-dressing escape was Latter Revealed To be that he was called 'by a senior official of an intelligence agency with whom he has been in touch for a long time' (Aziz admitted that he and his brother Ghazi had done this many times before when they were declared wanted by the government). Since this man could not enter into the mosque to meet him. He asked Maulana Aziz to come down to Aabpara police station, situated on a walking distance from the mosque and asked him to wear a burqa to avoid identification.<ref>http://www.atimes.com/atimes/South_Asia/IG07Df01.html</ref>
==Release== Aziz was released on 16 April 2009 by the Pakistani supreme court as he awaited trial on Alleged charges of murder, incitement, and kidnapping. He was greeted by throngs of supporters.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/apr/17/red-mosque-pakistan-cleric-bail |title=Red Mosque siege leader walks free to hero's welcome |first=Declan |last=Walsh |date=17 April 2009 |work=The Guardian |accessdate=14 November 2010}}</ref>
Since 2001, 27 different cases have been filed unsuccessfully against him.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dawn.com/news/1045051/lal-masjid-cleric-acquitted-in-all-cases |title=Lal Masjid cleric acquitted in all cases |first=Malik |last=Asad |date=24 September 2013 |work=[[Dawn News]] |accessdate=22 October 2015}}</ref>
