{{notability|org|date=July 2016}} The '''Dith Pran Holocaust Awareness Project''' is an American non-profit organization, founded in 1994 by [[Killing Fields]] survivor [[Dith Pran]] to educate the world about the [[genocide]] that took place in [[Cambodia]] during the reign of the [[Khmer Rouge rule of Cambodia|Khmer Rouge]] from 1975 to 1979.<ref name="Britannica">{{cite book|title=Britannica Book of the Year 2009|publisher=Encyclopædia Britannica, Inc.|isbn=9781593392321|page=124|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IaecAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA124&dq=Dith+Pran+Holocaust+Awareness&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjtpIjMjvbNAhUMWj4KHdeJAH0Q6AEIKDAC#v=onepage&q=Dith%20Pran%20Holocaust%20Awareness&f=false|language=en}}</ref> The organization also keeps photographic records to help Cambodians who are searching for missing family members.<ref name="Bartrop">{{cite book|last1=Bartrop|first1=Paul Robert|title=A Biographical Encyclopedia of Contemporary Genocide: Portraits of Evil and Good|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=9780313386787|page=74|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BleF7tl_rbUC&pg=PA74&dq=Dith+Pran+Holocaust+Awareness&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjtpIjMjvbNAhUMWj4KHdeJAH0Q6AEISTAI#v=onepage&q=Dith%20Pran%20Holocaust%20Awareness&f=false|language=en}}</ref> Dith Pran headed the organization until his death in 2008, when his widow Kim DePaul assumed that position.
