The [[Hawaii]] '''Gas Cap Law''' is a [[state law]] setting a [[price ceiling]] on [[wholesale]] [[gasoline]] prices, the maximum amount that may be charged for producing gasoline and delivering it to a [[filling station|service station]]. Under the law, the gas cap was set weekly by the [[Hawaii Public Utilities Commission]] (PUC) based on average [[spot price]]s for regular unleaded gasoline in three U.S. markets, [[New York Harbor]], the [[Gulf Coast]], and [[Los Angeles]].

The gas cap had a baseline price that is the same throughout Hawaii, but the total wholesale price varied depending on seven zones, reflecting the differing costs of delivery to various locations throughout the state.
{{div col|colwidth=30em}}
*(Zone 1) [[Oahu]]
*(Zone 2) [[Kauai]]
*(Zone 3) [[Maui]]
*(Zone 4) [[Hana, Hawaii|Hana]]
*(Zone 5) [[Molokai]]
*(Zone 6) [[Lanai]]
*(Zone 7) [[Hilo]]
*(Zone 8) [[Kona District, Hawaii|Kona]]
{{div col end}}

==Law suspended==
{{Update|inaccurate=yes|date=October 2011}}
On May 5, 2006, Gov. [[Linda Lingle]] (in office, 2002-2010) signed a bill suspending the gas cap law.  The bill allows Hawaii's governor to reinstate the gas cap law at any time.<ref>May 5, 2006. [http://www.thehawaiichannel.com/news/9170114/detail.html?rss=hon&psp=news "Lingle Signs Bill To Repeal Gas Cap".] [http://www.kitv.com KITV News]. Accessed August 2011.</ref>

