{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}} {{Use British English|date=January 2014}} The '''Land Settlement Association''' was a UK Government scheme set up in 1934, with help from the charities the [[Plunkett Foundation]] and the [[Carnegie United Kingdom Trust|Carnegie Trust]], to re-settle unemployed workers from depressed industrial areas,<ref name=Reading>[http://www.reading.ac.uk/merl/research/merl-landsettlement_1.aspx "Land Settlement Association"], University of Reading. Retrieved 18 August 2011</ref> particularly from [[North-East England]] and Wales. Between 1934 and 1939 1,100 [[Smallholding#Smallholdings in Britain|small-holdings]] were established within 26 [[Human settlement|settlements]].<ref>[http://www.peterclarke.com/index.html "The Land Settlement Association (LSA) The return of the unemployed to the land. 1934 – 1939"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100225130858/http://www.peterclarke.com/index.html |date=25 February 2010 }}, Dr Peter Clarke. Retrieved 18 August 2011</ref><ref>[http://www.northamptonsq.com/lsa/info "Land Settlement Association"], Northampton Square. Retrieved 18 August 2011</ref><ref>Clarke, Peter; [http://www.northamptonsq.com/ "The Land Settlement Association returned nearly 1,000 unemployed men to the land in the 1930s"], Northampton Square, 29 July 2011. Retrieved 18 August 2011</ref> [[File:Cottage on South Road - geograph.org.uk - 1597004.jpg|200px|right|thumb|LSA cottage at The Abingtons]] Settlements were set up in rural areas where each successful applicant’s family would be given a small-holding of approximately {{convert|5|acre|km2}}, livestock and a newly built cottage. Small-holdings were grouped in communities which were expected to run agricultural production as [[cooperative]] [[market garden]]s, with materials bought and produce sold exclusively through the Association. Applicants were [[Vetting|vetted]] and given agricultural training before being assigned a property.<ref name=Reading/><ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cAQwZarA58c</ref>
The allocation of settlements to the unemployed was suspended at the outbreak of the Second World War through the necessity of increasing food production; favour was given to those already with [[Horticulture|horticultural]] skills.<ref>[https://www.theyworkforyou.com/debates/?id=1939-11-23a.1370.6 "Land Settlement Association. Oral Answers to Questions — Unemployment"] (All Commons debates on 23 Nov 1939); TheyWorkForYou.com. Retrieved 18 August 2011</ref> After the war the Association was incorporated within a [[County council#United Kingdom|County Council]] scheme for statutory provision of smallholdings designed as a first step for those going into agricultural production.<ref name=Clarke>[http://www.peterclarke.com/Land4.htm "Land Settlement Association"], peterclarke.com (Dr Peter Clarke). Retrieved 18 August 2011</ref> The scheme was wound-up and all the properties privatised in 1983, by which time it was producing roughly 40% of English home grown salad crops.<ref name=Reading/><ref>[http://www.darkoptimism.org/ELC-CS.pdf "The Land Battle"] Shaun Chamberlin, ''Country Smallholding'', January 2013. Retrieved 24 May 2015</ref> The residual assets of the scheme were constituted as the LSA Charitable Trust,<ref>[http://lsact.wordpress.com "LSA Charitable Trust website"]. Retrieved 28 December 2012</ref> for the benefit of former tenants and to promote horticultural education.<ref>[http://www.grantsforhorticulturists.org.uk/LSA.html "LSA Charitable Trust (Guidance Notes)"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110528100955/http://www.grantsforhorticulturists.org.uk/LSA.html |date=28 May 2011 }} Grants for Horticulturists. Retrieved 29 June 2012</ref> {{clear left}} ==Settlements== Land Settlement Association settlements included: {{div col|colwidth=18em}} *[[Abbotts Ann]],<ref>[http://www.little-ann.co.uk/land%20settlement.htm "The Land Settlement Association and Little Park"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120118121652/http://www.little-ann.co.uk/land%20settlement.htm |date=18 January 2012 }}, Abbots Ann and Little Ann web site. Retrieved 18 August 2011</ref> *[[Boverton]],<ref>[http://unionhistory.info/timeline/Tl_Display.php?irn=100173 "Boverton Land Settlement scheme"], TUC History Online. Retrieved 18 August 2011</ref> *[[Broadwath]]<ref name=CCCA>[http://www.archiveweb.cumbria.gov.uk/dserve/dserve.exe?dsqIni=Dserve.ini&dsqApp=Archive&dsqCmd=Show.tcl&dsqDb=Catalog&dsqSearch=Term==%27Land%27&dsqPos=149 "Land Settlement Association"], Cumbria County Council - Archives. Retrieved 18 August 2011</ref> *[[Crofton, Cumbria|Crofton]]<ref name=CCCA/><ref>[http://www.visitoruk.com/historydetail.php?id=27106&cid=592&f=Carlisle "Crofton"], visitoruk.com. Retrieved 18 August 2011</ref> *[[Dalston, Cumbria|Dalston]]<ref name=CCCA/><ref>Burdett, Anna; [http://www.cumberlandnews.co.uk/farming/whatever-happened-to-cumbrian-strawberries-1.582837?referrerPath=farming/1m-marketing-push-to-take-cheese-to-top-1.754441 "Whatever Happened to Cumbriam Strawberries"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120324011218/http://www.cumberlandnews.co.uk/farming/whatever-happened-to-cumbrian-strawberries-1.582837?referrerPath=farming%2F1m-marketing-push-to-take-cheese-to-top-1.754441 |date=24 March 2012 }}, ''The Cumberland News'' 21 July 2009. Retrieved 18 August 2011</ref> *[[Dunstable]],<ref>Walded, R. (1999); ''Streets Ahead: An Illustrated Guide to the Street Names of Dunstable''; pp.&nbsp;266–268, 275, 282; The Book Castle; {{ISBN|1-871199-59-X}}</ref> *Elmesthorpe *[[Fen Drayton]],<ref>[http://www.scambs.gov.uk/Environment/Planning/DistrictPlanning/LocalDevelopmentFramework/SPDs/FenDraytonSPD.htm "Fen Drayton Former Land Settlement Association Estate SPD"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927074338/http://www.scambs.gov.uk/Environment/Planning/DistrictPlanning/LocalDevelopmentFramework/SPDs/FenDraytonSPD.htm |date=27 September 2011 }}, South Cambridgeshire District Council. Retrieved 18 August 2011</ref><ref>[http://www.cambridge-news.co.uk/Home/New-zero-carbon-homes-vision-for-village-settlement.htm "New zero-carbon homes vision for village settlement"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101022062913/http://www.cambridge-news.co.uk/Home/New-zero-carbon-homes-vision-for-village-settlement.htm |date=22 October 2010 }}, ''Cambridge News'' 18 October 2010. Retrieved 18 August 2011</ref> *[[Lawford]] and [[Ardleigh]],<ref> Bercaw, Louise Oldham; "Bibliography on Land Utilization 1918-36"; p.&nbsp;1011 </ref> *[[Londonthorpe|Harrowby]],<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/history/domesday/dblock/GB-492000-333000/page/3 "The Harrowby Land Settlement"], ''Domesday Reloaded'', BBC. Retrieved 18 August 2011</ref> *[[Low Fulney]],<ref>[http://www.pastscape.org.uk/hob.aspx?hob_id=916111&sort=4&search=all&criteria=Low%20Fulney&rational=q&recordsperpage=10 "Thornholme Grange"], ''National Monuments Record''. English Heritage. Retrieved 18 August 2011</ref> *[[Newbourne]],<ref>Sloane, Rachel; [http://www.bbc.co.uk/suffolk/content/articles/2007/10/26/newbourne_visit_feature.shtml "Newbourne"], BBC: Suffolk, 11 June 2008. Retrieved 18 August 2011</ref> *[[Newent]],<ref>[http://www.balh.co.uk/tlh/review.php?iID=84&rID=3 "A History of the County of Gloucester vol.12 Newent and May Hill"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111002034155/http://www.balh.co.uk/tlh/review.php?iID=84&rID=3 |date=2 October 2011 }}, British Association for Local History: "The Land Settlement Association also built 57 chalet bungalows from 1937 on an estate at The Scarr, Newent, most of which retain their distinctive appearance". Retrieved 18 August 2011</ref> *[[Oxcroft]],<ref>[https://www.victoriacountyhistory.ac.uk/explore/items/oxcroft-settlement "The Oxcroft Settlement"], ''Victoria County History'', "The Oxcroft Settlement was the only project of its kind in Derbyshire, and one of only two in England initiated by a county council". Retrieved 7 November 2017</ref> *[[Potton]],<ref name=Clarke/> *[[Sidlesham]],<ref>[http://www.sussex-opc.org/Kelly1938/SidleshamKellys1938.htm "Sidlesham, West Sussex"], ''Kelly's Directory'' 1938: "During 1935, 800 acres of land were acquired by the Land Settlement Association Ltd. To provide smallholdings for men from the distressed areas of Northumberland & Durham". Retrieved 18 August 2011</ref> *[[The Abingtons, Cambridgeshire|The Abingtons]],<ref>[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=66703 "Great and Little Abington"], ''British History Online'', para 5: "In Great Abington from the 1930s the Land Settlement Association built c. 45 houses to a standard design along roads laid out across the middle of the parish". Retrieved 18 August 2011</ref> *[[Wyboston, Chawston and Colesden]]<ref>[http://www.wccparish.co.uk/plan.htm#chawston "Chawston"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111007225415/http://www.wccparish.co.uk/plan.htm |date=7 October 2011 }}, Wyboston, Chawston and Colesden Parish, Community Web Site. Retrieved 18 August 2011</ref> {{div col end}}
